1 A BILL for an Act to amend and reenact sections 11-09.1-04 and 40-05.1-05 of the North Dakota
2 Century Code, relating to supersession of state laws in home rule counties and cities.
3 BE IT ENACTED BY THE LEGISLATIVE ASSEMBLY OF NORTH DAKOTA:
4 SECTION 1. AMENDMENT. Section 11-09.1-04 of the North Dakota Century Code is
5 amended and reenacted as follows:
6 11-09.1-04. Ratification by majority vote - Supersession of existing charter and
7 conflictingOrdinances in conflict with state laws void - Filing of copies of new charter.
8 If a majority of the qualified electors voting on the charter at the election vote in favor of the
9 home rule charter, it is ratified and becomes the organic law of the county on the first day of
10 January or July next following the election, and extends to all its county matters. The charter
11 and the ordinances made pursuant to the charter in county matters must be liberally construed
12 to supersede within the territorial limits and jurisdiction of the county any conflicting state law
13 except for any state law as it applies to cities or any power of a city to govern its own affairs,
14 without the consent of the governing body of the cityAny ordinance enacted or adopted by a
15 county under a home rule charter in conflict with state law is void. The charter may not authorize
16 the enactment of ordinances to diminish the authority of a board of supervisors of a township or
17 to change the structure of township government in any organized civil township, without the
18 consent of the board of supervisors of the township. NoAn ordinance of a home rule county
19 shallmay not supersede sections 49-22-16 and 49-22.1-13. One copy of the charter as ratified
20 and approved must be filed with the secretary of state; one with the recorder for the county,
21 unless the board of county commissioners designates a different official; and one with the
22 auditor of the county to remain as a part of its permanent records. Courts shall take judicial
23 notice of the charter.
